  "original_title": "Sri Lanka cabinet writes off over Rs.1.5 billion paddy farming loans",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Sri Lanka cabinet writes off over Rs.1.5 billion paddy farming loans",
      "author": "Dulya de Silva",
      "body_lines": [
        "ECONOMYNEXT \u2013 Sri Lanka Cabinet has approved a proposal to write off over 1.5 billion rupees worth loans for paddy farmers who were hit by the 2019 Easter Sunday attacks and COVID 19 outbreak, a spokesman said, as the country\u2019s economic crisis had left many of them unable to repay.",
        "The Cabinet of Ministers had approved for the proposal for paddy farmers who have 2 hectares of land or less.",
        "Cabinet Spokesman Bandula Gunawardena said over 95% or one million paddy farmers have land of 2 hectare of less than that and most of their loans from Bank of Ceylon, People\u2019s Bank, Regional Development Bank and National Savings Bank \u2013 all state banks \u2013 will be written off.",
        "\u201cAs of May 31, there is a 1,231 million rupee loan out of total 1,996 million given to paddy farmers have not been paid. In addition to this, around 274 million of interest payment and penalty also have not been paid by the paddy farmers. All these unpaid loans will be written off,\u201d Gunawardena told the weekly cabinet briefing on Tuesday (05).",
        "He said the move was to encourage all the paddy farmers to resume paddy cultivation again in the next season.",
        "A government document released on Tuesday July 5 showed that the ongoing economic crisis has made it difficult to repay the loans. Farmers account for 30% of the population.",
        "\u201cThe economic crisis in the country caused by the Easter Sunday attack and the subsequent Covid-19 epidemic situation is further intensifying,\u201d the government document said.",
        "It added that farmers were also adversely affected by President Gotabaya Rajapaksa\u2019s overnight decision to force the farmers to switch to organic fertilizer which was done bid to go for only organic cultivation in the country. But the move failed and the ban, which was imposed in April last year was lifted in November.",
        "\u201cDue to this situation, the farmers have defaulted in repayment of loans taken for paddy cultivation. Banks have classified those loans as non-performing loans. Due to this reason, many farmers may be ineligible for the loans required for paddy cultivation in the upcoming reason.\u201d",
        "\u201cTherefore, it is essential to provide relief to them through the intervention of the government. waive of the principal loans from the government banks for the cultivation of paddy on land of 2 Harare or less,\u201d",
        "The fertilizer ban has culminated in what experts call Sri Lanka\u2019s worst performing Agricultural season in over a decade, and an acute food shortage intensified by supply chain disruptions which have resulted in expensive food prices.",
        "The production of rice, Sri Lanka\u2019s staple food, was down 40 percent in the last Maha season.",
        "The island\u2019s government is scrambling to increase output, allocating unutilised land for agricultural activities and encouraging state workers to engage in home gardening. (Colombo/July 06/2022)"
      ],
